ASP.NET MVC uses routing to establish URL patterns and make them SEO-friendly.
You can accomplish this using Route attributes or a RouteConfig class.


ROUTE ATTRIBUTE

Prefix Controller on the HomeController class is automatically appended,
reducing redundancy.

[Route("properties")]
public class HomeController : Controller
{
    [HttpGet("details/{id}")]
    public ActionResult Details(int id)
    {
        // Your logic here
    }
}


This will generate a URL as follows:

 * Action Method: public ActionResult Details(int id)
 * Route Attribute: [HttpGet("details/{id}")]
 * URL: https://example.com/properties/details/123


ROUTECONFIG CLASS

Define a route template within RouteConfig.cs following the RESTful convention.

public static void RegisterRoutes(RouteCollection routes)
{
    routes.IgnoreRoute("{resource}.axd/{*pathInfo}");

    routes.MapRoute(
        name: "PropertyDetails",
        url: "properties/details/{id}",
        defaults: new { controller = "Home", action = "Details", id = UrlParameter.Optional }
    );

    routes.MapRoute(
        name: "Default",
        url: "{controller}/{action}/{id}",
        defaults: new { controller = "Home", action = "Index", id = UrlParameter.Optional }
    );
}


When running on the local server, RouteConfig often handles routing; however,
it's common to use both methods.

The built-in Dependency Injection (DI) container in ASP.NET Core is a
lightweight, feature-rich tool that simplifies and streamlines app development.


BENEFITS OF ASP.NET CORE'S DI CONTAINER

 * Uniformity: The DI container ensures a consistent pattern for managing
   dependencies across the application, reducing the chances of errors and
   streamlining maintenance.

 * Decoupling: Using the DI container facilitates loose coupling between
   classes, making your application modular and easier to manage.

 * Testability: DI promotes writing testable code by enabling dependency
   injection in both production and testing environments.

 * Flexibility: It's easy to replace the default container with another library
   such as AutoFac or SimpleInjector if specific project requirements demand it.

 * Simplicity: The container is intuitive to use, requiring minimal
   configuration. This makes it an excellent choice for rapid application
   development.

 * Scoping: The container provides different levels of service lifetimes:
   transient, scoped, and singleton, ensuring services are created and disposed
   of in a consistent and optimized manner.

 * Efficiency: The built-in container is lightweight and optimized for
   performance, making it a suitable and efficient choice for most applications.

 * Security and Reliability: Leveraging the tools and updates provided by the
   ASP.NET Core team enhances platform security and stability.

 * Simplified Configuration: With Visual Studio, access to the DI container is
   integrated seamlessly, simplifying the setup of services and dependencies.


CODE EXAMPLE: USING DI IN ASP.NET CORE

Here is the ASP.NET Core MVC code:

// Startup.cs
public void ConfigureServices(IServiceCollection services)
{
    // Register your services here
    services.AddTransient<ITransientService, TransientService>();
    services.AddScoped<IScopedService, ScopedService>();
    services.AddSingleton<ISingletonService, SingletonService>();
    services.AddTransient<IRepository, Repository>();
}

public void Configure(IApplicationBuilder app, IWebHostEnvironment env)
{
    // Other middleware setup
    app.UseEndpoints(endpoints =>
    {
        endpoints.MapControllerRoute(
            name: "default",
            pattern: "{controller=Home}/{action=Index}/{id?}");
    });
}

// HomeController.cs
public class HomeController : Controller
{
    private readonly ITransientService _transientService;
    private readonly IScopedService _scopedService;
    private readonly ISingletonService _singletonService;
    private readonly IRepository _repository;

    public HomeController(ITransientService transientService, IScopedService scopedService, 
            ISingletonService singletonService, IRepository repository)
    {
        _transientService = transientService;
        _scopedService = scopedService;
        _singletonService = singletonService;
        _repository = repository;
    }

    public IActionResult Index()
    {
        // Use the injected services
        return View();
    }
}

In ASP.NET Core, configurations are stored centrally in the
\texttt{appsettings.json} file. They can be environment-specific, a feature that
ensures different settings for development, staging, and production
environments.

Developers can access these configurations using the Configuration object, which
is loaded into the DI container.


BEST PRACTICES FOR CONFIGURATIONS

 * appsettings.json: This file contains common configurations across all
   environments.
 * appsettings.{Environment}.json: Configuration files specific to each
   environment.
 * User Secrets Configuration: For local development, secrets such as connection
   strings and API keys can be kept in a separate secrets.json file. The content
   of this file is never pushed to the source control repository.


ICONFIGURATION INTERFACE

The IConfiguration interface represents a set of key/value application
configuration properties. It provides methods such as GetSection and GetValue to
fetch specific configurations.

public class HomeController : Controller
{
    private readonly IConfiguration _configuration;

    public HomeController(IConfiguration configuration)
    {
        _configuration = configuration;
    }

    public IActionResult Index()
    {
        // Access a configuration key
        var someConfig = _configuration.GetValue<string>("SomeConfigKey");

        return View();
    }
}



ACCESSING CONFIGURATIONS

 * Strongly Typed: Create a custom settings class that corresponds to the JSON
   structure, making it easier to access and maintain configurations.

Here's a code example:

public class CustomSettings
{
    public string SomeKey { get; set; }
}


In the Startup.cs file, use the ConfigureServices method to load settings into
the DI container:

services.Configure<CustomSettings>(_configuration.GetSection("CustomSection"));


Then, in the controller, inject IOptions<CustomSettings> to access the settings:

public class HomeController : Controller
{
    private readonly CustomSettings _customSettings;

    public HomeController(IOptions<CustomSettings> customSettings)
    {
        _customSettings = customSettings.Value;
    }

    public IActionResult Index()
    {
        var someSetting = _customSettings.SomeKey;
        return View();
    }
}


 * IHostingEnvironment: Access the current environment using the
   IHostingEnvironment interface, which provides properties such as
   EnvironmentName.


USER SECRETS

The dotnet user-secrets tool is a secure and easily accessible method for
storing sensitive data during development.

You can add keys and values using the CLI:

dotnet user-secrets set "SomeKey" "SecretValue"


To access User Secrets in your project, you can use IConfiguration as you
normally would. If SomeKey exists in both User Secrets and any other
configuration source, the value from User Secrets overrides others during local
development.

user-secrets is useful for managing sensitive information such as API keys and
connection strings in your development environment. However, it's essential to
remember that user-secrets are intended only for use during development and
should not be used in a production environment.

Azure Key Vault ensures a secure and managed way to safeguard sensitive
information by leveraging keys, secrets, and certificates. In your application,
you can use the App Service Configuration to access these key vault references.

Maintaining ASP.NET MVC applications can be challenging, especially as the
codebase and team grow. Here is the key strategies to optimize such applications
for maintainability:


KEY STRATEGIES

 * Decomposition into Areas: Use Areas to segment related functionality. This
   helps in code organization, especially in large applications.

 * Namespaces: Employ namespaces to logically group classes and simplify finding
   components.

 * Areas of Responsibility: Keep separation of concerns within various
   components. Controllers should primarily handle user input and HTTP requests,
   while Models represent data logic and Views are responsible for the user
   interface.

 * Avoid Complex Routing Logic: Overly intricate routing can make it challenging
   to predict where an action will lead. Employ simple, straightforward, and
   predictable routing whenever possible.

 * Properly Segmented Views: Use partial views and child actions in the
   appropriate scenarios. Don't render widgets, or similar items, in main parent
   views that introduce coupling between different parts of your code.

 * Data Interaction Through Models: Use Models to manage data and define
   business logic. This not only aids in structuring your codebase but also
   centralizes data management, improving maintainability.


CODE EXAMPLE: PROPER DATA HANDLING IN ASP.NET MVC

Here is the C# code:

public class EmployeeController : Controller
{
    private readonly IEmployeeRepository _employeeRepository;

    public EmployeeController(IEmployeeRepository employeeRepository)
    {
        _employeeRepository = employeeRepository;
    }

    public ActionResult Edit(int id)
    {
        var employee = _employeeRepository.GetEmployeeById(id);

        // Pass the employee object to the view for editing
        return View(employee);
    }

    [HttpPost]
    public ActionResult Edit(Employee employee)
    {
        if (ModelState.IsValid)
        {
            // Validate and update the employee through the repository
            _employeeRepository.UpdateEmployee(employee);

            // Redirect to the employee list after successful update
            return RedirectToAction("Index");
        }

        // If the model is not valid, return to the edit view with the current model
        return View(employee);  
    }
}

Real-time web functionality often involves establishing persistent connections
from browser-based clients to servers. Traditionally, HTTP has been limited to
request-response actions, and to overcome this restriction, SignalR, a library
for ASP.NET, was developed.

By leveraging SignalR in your ASP.NET MVC applications, you can easily achieve
bidirectional communication between clients and servers with minimal
codeâ€”offering a seamless user experience.


CORE COMPONENTS OF SIGNALR

HUBS

 * Server-side classes that clients interact with.
 * Exposed server methods can be invoked by clients.
 * Expose public strong-typed client methods that can be called from the server.

CONNECTIONS

 * Represents a persistent connection between the client and server.
 * Clients initiate connections and can send messages to the server.


SIGNALR WORKFLOW

 1. Hub Creation: Define hubs on the server to handle client-server
    communication.
 2. Client Connection: Establish and manage a connection from the client to the
    server.
 3. Communication: Use hubs to invoke methods on clients and retrieve responses.


KEY SIGNALR COMPONENTS

 * Connection API: Configures the connection between the client and server,
   providing capabilities like connection event handling, connection state
   management, and custom query string support.
 * HubConnection: Represents a connection to a hub on the server.


ESTABLISHING A SIGNALR CONNECTION

SignalR connections are managed through JavaScript:

 1. Configuration: Customize the connection through options like transport mode
    and connection timeout, and enable features such as automatic reconnection.
 2. Event Handling: Utilize connection events for error handling and to respond
    to connection state changes. Common events include onConnected,
    onReconnecting, and onClosed.
 3. Start and Stop: Call start to initiate the connection, and stop to terminate
    it when necessary.

// Configure the connection
var connection = new signalR.HubConnectionBuilder()
    .withUrl("/chatHub")
    .build();

// Manage connection events
connection.on("ReceiveMessage", (user, message) => {
    // Display message in UI
});
connection.start().catch(err => console.error(err.toString()));



CODE EXAMPLE: SIMPLE CHAT APPLICATION

Here is an example:

 1. Server-side Hub that echoes messages back to all clients.
 2. Client-side HTML to send and display messages with the server.


SERVER-SIDE SIGNALR HUB

C#

using Microsoft.AspNetCore.SignalR;

public class ChatHub : Hub
{
    public async Task SendMessage(string user, string message)
    {
        await Clients.All.SendAsync("ReceiveMessage", user, message);
    }
}



CLIENT-SIDE HTML AND JAVASCRIPT SETUP

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Chat</title>
    <script src="https://code.jquery.com/jquery-3.3.1.min.js"></script>
    <script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/@microsoft/signalr@latest/dist/browser/signalr.min.js"></script>
    <script>
        $(document).ready(function () {
            var connection = new signalR.HubConnectionBuilder()
                .withUrl("/chathub")
                .configureLogging(signalR.LogLevel.Information)
                .build();

            connection.on("ReceiveMessage", function (user, message) {
                var msg = user + " says: " + message;
                var li = document.createElement("li");
                li.textContent = msg;
                $("#discussion").append(li);
            });

            connection.start()
                .then(function () {
                    $("#sendButton").click(function () {
                        var user = $("#userInput").val();
                        var message = $("#messageInput").val();
                        connection.invoke("SendMessage", user, message).catch(function (err) {
                            return console.error(err.toString());
                        });
                    });
                })
                .catch(function (err) {
                    return console.error(err.toString());
                });
        });
    </script>
</head>
<body>
    <input type="text" id="userInput" />
    <input type="text" id="messageInput" />
    <input type="button" id="sendButton" value="SEND" />
    <ul id="discussion"></ul>
</body>
</html>
